[[File:Cartel de distancias en Abra del Acay.jpg|thumb|Nevado de Acay from Abra de Acay]]
{{coord|24|25|S|66|10|W|display=intitle|notes={{sfn|U.S. Geological Survey|1984|p=1129}}}}
'''Nevado de Acay''' is a {{convert|5950|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} mountain in [[Argentina]]. It is a [[Intrusive rock|volcanic intrusion]] that formed during the [[Miocene]] and was later exposed. The intrusion is formed by [[monzonite]] and is associated with a [[Fault (geology)|fault]] system that also connects to neighbouring volcanoes.

While not presently [[Glacier|glaciated]], it contains a seasonal [[snowpack]] and is the source of several streams and rivers, including the [[Salado River (Argentina)|Rio Salado]]. A number of archeological sites have been found on Nevado de Acay and mining activity occurred there until recent times.

== Geology ==

Nevado de Acay is {{convert|5716|m}},<ref name="MartiniStrelin2013" /> {{convert|5886|m}}{{sfn|U.S. Geological Survey|1984|p=1129}} or {{convert|5950|m}} high.{{sfn|Morello|Matteucci|Rodriguez|Silva|2012|p=17}}{{sfn|U.S. Geological Survey|1984|p=1129}} It lies in the [[La Poma Department]] of [[Argentina]]'s [[Salta Province]]. It is part of the Cuesta del Acay mountains and their highest summit.{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=8}} The Calchaqui valley extends south from Nevado de Acay.{{sfn|Paoli|2003|p=10}}

It is formed by [[monzonite]] that was generated 12.6 ± 0.3 million years ago,<ref name="InselGrove2012" /> along the Calchaqui fault.{{sfn|del Papa|Petrinovic|2017|p=197}} It originally formed as an [[intrusion]] that was exposed about 12.61 ± 0.25 million years ago.{{sfn|del Papa|Petrinovic|2017|p=199}} Another date is 26 million years ago,{{sfn|Coira|Kay|Viramonte|1993|p=686}} which would make it contemporaneous with the disintegration of the [[Farallon Plate]] and the following increase in [[subduction]] and volcanic activity.{{sfn|Coira|Kay|Viramonte|1993|p=710}} Yet another older date is 18.9 million years ago.<ref name="PetrinovicRiller2005" />

Emplaced within the [[Precambrian]]-[[Cambrian]] Puncoviscana [[formation (geology)|formation]], the Nevado de Acay monzonite contains [[biotite]], [[diorite]], [[hornblende]], [[magnetite]], [[monzodiorite]], [[pyroxene]], [[titanite]] and [[tonalite]]. [[Skarn]] and mineral deposits formed within the monzonite as well.{{sfn|Coira|Kay|Viramonte|1993|p=686}}

Located close to the [[Negra Muerta volcanic complex]], it is a volcanic system associated with the Calama-Olacapato-El Toro [[fault (geology)|fault]] system. Other volcanoes such as [[Aguas Calientes caldera|Aguas Calientes]] and [[Incahuasi Sur]] are associated with this fault system.<ref name="PetrinovicRiller2005" />

[[Cirque]]s indicate the presence of former glaciers.<ref name="Martonne1934" /> The present-day [[snowline]] lies at an altitude of {{convert|5800|m}};{{sfn|U.S. Geological Survey|1984|p=1128}} [[rock glacier]]s fed by avalanches exist on Nevado de Acay in [[Pleistocene]] glacier valleys.{{sfn|U.S. Geological Survey|1984|p=1139}} Nevado de Acay is covered in snow only during the winter months, although summer storms can also deposit snow on it; during the dry season the mountain is bare.{{sfn|Morello|Matteucci|Rodriguez|Silva|2012|p=17}}

The {{Interlanguage link multi|Calchaqui River|es|3=Río Calchaquí}} originates on Nevado de Acay and flows south,{{sfn|Paoli|2003|p=39}}{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=84}} as does the [[Rio Juramento]].{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=278}} Other waterbodies originating on Nevado de Acay are the Arroyo Pircas, a tributary to the Rio Juramento,{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=386}} Arroyo Tastil which flows into Arroyo del Toro,{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=483}} which also originates on Nevado de Acay and eventually flows into the Arroyo Arias;{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=491}} Arroyo Arias in turn also drains into the Juramento.{{sfn|Marrazzo|1921|p=39}} Most streams in the area are fed with [[meltwater]]. The mountains form the [[drainage divide]]; water flowing to the west eventually ends up in various [[endorheic]] basins.{{sfn|Morello|Matteucci|Rodriguez|Silva|2012|p=17}} The [[Rio Los Patos]] also originates on Nevado de Acay and archeological sites are found on its river terraces,{{sfn|Mignone|2015|p=375}} and it converges with the [[Rio San Antonio de los Cobres]], which likewise originates on Nevado de Acay as [[Rio Organullo]] and after passing close to [[San Antonio del los Cobres]] and receiving the Quebrada Potrerillos carries the name of the town, and eventually reach [[Salinas Grandes (Jujuy and Salta)|Salinas Grandes]] where they evaporate.{{sfn|Paoli|2003|p=102}}

== Biology ==

''[[Liolaemus multicolor]]'', an [[iguanid]] [[lizard]], has been found on Nevado de Acay.<ref name="Troncoso-Palacios2014" /> [[Endorheic]] basins in the valleys on Nevado de Acay were an important resource for the Las Cuevas V [[archeological site]], which belongs to a cultural horizont between 600 [[Anno Domini|BC]] - 400 [[AD]].<ref name="Feo2011" />

== Human activities ==
[[File:Mines on Nevado de Acay.jpg|thumb|Map of mines in a 1907 sketch]]
Nevado de Acay is the site of an [[Inca civilization|Inka]] mountain sanctuary.{{sfn|Morello|Matteucci|Rodriguez|Silva|2012|p=19}} A summit sanctuary was discovered in 2000; later two additional sites were discovered on the subsidiary summits Blanca and Navaja.{{sfn|Mignone|2015|p=377}} Some historical references to the mountain indicate that it was the connection between the Inka province Chicoana and the [[Altiplano|Puna]], although the [[Abra del Acay]] is not the only place to which these historical records may refer. The present day [[National Route 40 (Argentina)|National Route 40]] passes close to the mountain.<ref name="Mignone2014" />

The mountaintop was not the sole site of human activity at Nevado de Acay; traces of mining and pastoral activity among others has been found lower on its slopes as well. At least 53 structures have been identified at elevations between {{convert|4500|-|5000|m}}.<ref name="Mignone2014" /> Historical records exist of a site named "San Bernardo de Acay" south of Nevado de Acay.{{sfn|Mignone|2015|p=376}} The archeological structures of Nevado de Acay are still only incompletely understood.{{sfn|Mignone|2015|p=385}}

Some of these mines reported in 1907 are known as "Flor de Desierto", "Protectora", "Resurreccion" and "Saturno" - the last owner of these mines obtained them in 1924. Mining activity including [[gold]] and [[silver]] is reported to have occurred in the area during the time of [[Spanish Empire|Spanish]] rule and ended only during the 1656 rebellion of [[Pedro Bohórquez]]; the Spanish efforts on these mines may have been the reason why the rebellion occurred in the region. Later an [[iron]] mine was active on the northern slope but it is now abandoned.<ref name="Mignone2014" /> [[Obsidian]] outcrops have been observed in the area.<ref name="YacobaccioEscola2004" />

