'''Ratchet knife''' in [[Jamaica]] is a general type of folding knife, generally German-made, considered easy to open quickly and associated with "[[rude boy]]" masculinity,<ref name="Stolzoff2000">{{cite book|author=Norman C. Stolzoff|title=Wake the Town & Tell the People: Dancehall Culture in Jamaica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ph8TBR6LErQC&pg=PA81|year=2000|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-2514-4|pages=81–}}</ref> the [[Okapi (knife)|Okapi]] being a favourite brand.<ref name="Davis1985">{{cite book|author=Stephen Davis|title=Bob Marley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTowAQAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Schenkman Books|isbn=978-0-87047-045-5|page=49}} ''The major emblem of the rudie was his ratchet, a curved German gravity knife (Okapi was a favorite brand)'']</ref>

